         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">April 28/80 ¶ My dear Mueller ¶  ¶ There is variability in the color of various Cruciferae ¶  but I do not remember any of that from yellow to white, except Raphanus Raphanistrum &amp; the [Austn] Drabas ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.04.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4b, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Cyathea cunninghamii</seg> (MEL 224426), together with a note by J. G. Baker: '<seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">Cyathea affinis</hi>
                     </seg>, Swartz, is founded on <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">Polypodium affine</hi>
                     </seg>, Forst. There is a type specimen of Forsters plant in the herbarium of the British Museum, &amp; the description in the <seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">2nd</hi>
                     </seg> edition of Synopsis Filicum was drawn up from this specimen. It is totally different from this Australian Cyathea in cutting, texture &amp; involucre J. G. Baker.'</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0.1598in; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS embossed with crest of Royal Gardens Kew. MS annotation by M: 'Answ 18/6/80 FvM'.</p>
               </note>April 28/80</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is variability in the color of various <name key="Cruciferae">Cruciferae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 3 March 1880.</p>
               </note> but I do not remember any of that from yellow to white, except <name key="Raphanus%20Raphanistrum">Raphanus Raphanistrum</name> &amp; the [Austn] <name key="Draba">Draba</name>s as to which whether from hybridization or variation I cannot tell but in the Herbm it seems impossible always to define the golden from the white [fld.] except by color of flower.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Of course you know how variable Cheiranthi are</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As to your Polypodium Mr Baker has carefully examined it again &amp; regards it as a mere state of Nephrod. decompositum wanting the involucre &amp; he regards Pol. rufescens Blume as an analogous form of the less divided variety of the same species<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 3 March 1880.</p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever most sincy yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J D Hooker</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
